<HEADLINE>
FT  29 FEB 92 / TGWU starts ban on overtime at Vauxhall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS OF the TGWU general workers' union at Vauxhall, the General Motors
subsidiary, began an overtime ban yesterday in an effort to persuade the
company to improve a pay offer.
Other unions - including the AEU engineering workers' organisation - are
expected to order members to refuse overtime work within the next few days.
The Vauxhall offer to 9,000 manual workers would provide 5 per cent rises
from October last year and an increase in line with inflation from this
October, plus a single unconsolidated payment of 0.5 per cent of salary.
Employees at the Luton car assembly and parts plants would receive an extra
5 per cent on meeting demands for changes in work practices and bargaining
procedures.
The unions are angry that Vauxhall has refused to concede a reduction in the
39-hour week. They say the proposed deal is worth less than that won
recently by Ford workers.
</TEXT>
