<HEADLINE>
FT  29 FEB 92 / Morocco and EC pull back from brink
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOROCCO and the European Community last night pulled back from the brink of
a crisis, agreeing in last-minute talks in Rabat to extend a fishing pact.
The deal meant that 800 fishing vessels, mostly Spanish, could still fish in
Moroccan waters instead of pulling out by midnight last night.
Relations between Morocco and the EC ran into stormy weather after the
European Parliament voted down Ecu463m (Pounds 324m) in credit and aid under
a co-operation agreement, because of its human rights record.
Rabat responded by freezing the agreement with the EC and so jeopardising a
four-year fishing accord, which is vital to Spain's large fleet and due to
run out today.
As the fishing accord deadline neared, the EC ordered vessels in Moroccan
waters back to port from midnight.
But with both sides anxious to avoid a breach, a Brussels official - Mr
Manuel Marin, the EC commissioner for development and fisheries - flew to
Rabat yesterday evening for talks with cabinet ministers.
An EC spokesman in Brussels later announced: 'There's been an agreement to
prolong the deal for two months.'
There were indications of a change of heart in Rabat after EC foreign
ministers decided last week to explore a wider-ranging free trade agreement
with Morocco. The ministers are to discuss this possibility in Brussels on
Monday.
EC officials said the discussion would widen to examine similar agreements
with Morocco's neighbours, Algeria and Tunisia. What had seemed a tactical
ploy to mend diplomatic fences with Rabat could eventually widen into a
strategic aim to bind the Maghreb as a whole closer to the EC.
Morocco's creditor governments have agreed to allow the country to delay
payment on a large portion of its Dollars 22bn foreign debt, Reuter reports.
The agreement was reached at a meeting of the Paris Club of creditor
countries. Moroccan Finance Minister Mohammed Berrada said the agreement
allowed his country to reschedule Dollars 1.2bn.
</TEXT>
