<HEADLINE>
FT  29 FEB 92 / Gardening (Plant of the Week): Galanthus Atkinsii
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARTHUR HELLYER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is a snowdrop and, if I were confined to one variety only, this is the
one I would choose because it spread rapidly into fine colonies and it has
very fine flowers on long stems. Curiously, it produces no seeds and its
rapid increase is due to bulb multiplication, which means that it shows no
variation at all, but is always of the same uniform quality. It flowers in
February and early March, prefers semi-shaded places, but will grow in full
sun and is best planted immediately after flowering, when it can be lifted
with soil around its roots, divided into small clusters of bulbs and
replanted as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
