FT  28 FEB 92 / International Company News: Seven-Up files against Coca-Cola
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DALLAS-BASED Seven-Up Company, the soft drinks concentrates business,
has filed a multi-million dollar lawsuit against the rival Coca-Cola
Company, alleging that the latter has been attempting to disrupt Seven-Up's
arrangements with bottlers.
Formally, the suit alleges 'tortuous interference and other unlawful conduct
including certain misrepresentations' by Coca-Cola of bottlers who handle
both companies' products.
The case was filed in the state district court in Dallas on Wednesday. It
seeks unspecified compensatory damages, and punative damages of Dollars
500m. There was no immediate response from Coca-Cola, which ranks number one
in the soft drinks market, to the suit.
Seven-Up's chairman, Mr John Albers, said that the company would make no
further statement regarding the litigation. However, people who had read the
complaint said that it concerned the lemon-lime segment of the soft drinks
market, which Coca-Cola entered in 1960 with its Sprite brand.
In essence, the complaint alleges that Coca-Cola attempted to 'seduce'
bottlers away from Seven-Up, by projecting various 'false and misleading
impressions'. It cites one Texan bottler, for example, which it claims
ceased bottling for Seven-Up in January as a result.
</TEXT>
