FT  28 FEB 92 / International Company News: Net income at T-D Bank declines
5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TORONTO-DOMINION Bank has suffered a 5 per cent drop in first-quarter
earnings, confirming it is no longer the star performer among Canada's big
six banks.
T-D, harder hit by the recession than its main rivals, saw net income fall
to CDollars 115m (USDollars 96.6m) or 35 cents a share, from CDollars 126m
or 38 cents a year earlier.
Return on equity slipped to 8.6 per cent from 9.8 per cent, while return on
average assets fell to 0.68 per cent from 0.72 per cent. On international
business, the return on assets was 0.28 per cent, down from 0.58 per cent a
year earlier.
Loan loss provisions were unchanged at CDollars 120m, but the portfolio of
non-performing loans grew to CDollars 1.73bn from CDollars 1.34bn. A large
chunk of the increase stemmed from business in Australia.
The bank said net interest margin improved as lower interest rates widened
domestic loan spreads.
National Bank of Canada, smallest of the big six, reported first-quarter net
profit of CDollars 49.8m or 32 cents a share, down 9 per cent from CDollars
55.3m, or 36 cents, a year earlier, writes Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
The bank attributed the decline to the long recession, continuing high
loan-loss provisions and higher non-interest expenses, partly offset by
declining interest rates and good results from the investment banking and
brokerage subsidiary.
Return on equity was 11.3 per cent, against 13.4 per cent, and return on
average assets 0.53 per cent, compared with 0.60 per cent. Total assets at
January 31 were CDollars 37bn, against CDollars 36bn a year earlier.
