<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Attempt to jail Nadir postponed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ATTEMPT by creditors of Mr Asil Nadir, chairman of Polly Peck
International, to have him jailed for his alleged contempt of court has been
delayed.
The creditors, owed about Pounds 80m, allege that Mr Nadir broke an
undertaking to the court not to dispose of assets.
Yesterday Mr Anthony Scrivener QC, for Mr Nadir, argued that the undertaking
had ended by the time of the alleged breach and that there was therefore no
basis for the creditors' complaint.
Mr Justice Knox rejected that argument but gave Mr Nadir leave to challenge
his decision in the Court of Appeal, resulting in the contempt move being
postponed to a later date.
Earlier the judge had rejected a plea by Mr Scrivener that the contempt case
be heard in camera.
Mr Nadir has been sent for trial at the Old Bailey on 66 charges of theft
and false accounting, involving more than Pounds 100m.
</TEXT>
