<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Targets of pension trustees criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES of pension funds should set more demanding targets for their
investment managers, Mr Tim Congdon, economist at discount house Gerrard and
National, said yesterday.
Speaking at the National Association of Pension Funds annual investment
conference in Eastbourne, he criticised trustees for typically expecting
real long-term returns of only 4 per cent to 4.5 per cent, whereas the
economic expectation was for 6 per cent to 6.5 per cent.
'It is not surprising that there has been a tendency for funds to throw up
persistent surpluses,' he said. He was puzzled that companies had failed to
provide inflation-proofed benefits during the 1980s even though investment
returns had been very high.
He was less optimistic about the near future. The ratio of dividends to
gross domestic product was 'somewhat high', he said. The total return from
equity market investment could be expected in the 1990s to be 'somewhat
less' than the historic norm.
Mr David Tweedie, chairman of the Accounting Standards Board, called for the
support of fund managers in implementing accounting reforms.
'There will be a backlash against what we are doing,' he warned, giving as
an example protests by the banks against board proposals on accounting for
the balance-sheet effects of securitisation of loans.
He added that fund managers might value information in company accounts
about staff and training, but companies would be very resistant. 'You will
have to speak up if you want that,' he said.
</TEXT>
