<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Gloom over prospects for property companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS expect the number of property companies going into receivership to
rise, according to a survey carried out by Chesterton Financial, a property
adviser, and Chartered Surveyor Weekly magazine.
Three quarters of the lenders polled expect a higher rate of receiverships
over the next six months, and half of them expect the upward trend to
continue for at least a year.
The survey showed a sharp drop in confidence about the prospects of a quick
recovery. Only four of the 60 lending institutions surveyed expected an
improvement in the market over the next six months. Last July most banks
thought the market had bottomed out.
However, more than half expected it to improve over the year, while only
three thought it would get worse.
Lenders have increased their average bad debt provision by 8.5 per cent.
Provisions against bad debts are likely to be the norm for at least the next
six months. The proportion of borrowers from the 60 lenders who breached
their loan covenants has fallen by more than a fifth to 13.7 per cent.
Lenders remain pessimistic about problem debts, with 40 per cent expecting
more borrowers to break their loan covenants over the next year, contrasting
with 25 per cent who had that expectation last July.
Banks have delayed putting companies into receivership because of the
difficulties of selling into a depressed market. Mr Mike Riley, managing
director of Chesterton Financial, said: 'We expect to see an increased
number of receiverships as the market improves.'
The largest proportion of the banks and financial institutions surveyed was
based in the UK with the others based on the Continent, in Japan and the US.
Commercial Property Lending Confidence Barometer, Chesterton, 48-54 Brook
St, London W1A 2BU. Free.
</TEXT>
