<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Securities Institute launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PROFESSIONAL body for the securities industry, modelled on institutes in
the accountancy and legal professions, has been launched.
The Securities Institute aims to attract members of the London Stock
Exchange as well as people working in related fields such as investment
analysis, corporate finance and investment management.
The creation of the body is in part a reaction to the Big Bang reforms of
six years ago, when control of the exchange passed from individual
stockbrokers to securities firms. Since then, many brokers have bemoaned the
passing of the old 'club' spirit with the demise of the trading floor.
Mr Graham Ross Russell, chairman of the institute and a former deputy
chairman of the exchange, said he hoped that membership of the body would be
'useful for members' career prospects' and would give clients added
confidence in their advisers.
Unlike other professional bodies, the institute will not play a large role
in regulating its members. Statutory regulation passed under the Financial
Services Act from the exchange to the Securities and Futures Authority
(formerly The Securities Association), and this will remain the main
regulator for the industry.
</TEXT>
