<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Car VAT decision overturned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TRIBUNAL on value added tax has overturned a ruling by Customs and Excise
that the cost of cars provided by Co-operative Insurance Society to
employees is liable to the tax.
The tribunal ruled that VAT was not chargeable on the society's car scheme,
which offered employees the choice between a higher salary or a company car.
Customs and Excise has maintained that salary forgone in effect represents a
contribution towards renting the company car for partly private use. Renting
the car for purposes other than the job is a payment liable for VAT.
The society argued that its scheme was not equivalent to charging a cash sum
for the use of company cars but simply an element in the calculation of
salaries.
The society's arrangement is relatively unusual and may not apply directly
to other company car schemes because it offers employees a choice of two
employment contracts. The position for companies offering a single
employment contract with either option remains unclear. Several companies
and tax advisers have been awaiting the outcome to determine the structure
of car schemes.
Mr Mike Ward, society taxation manager, said: 'We are pleased with the
court's judgment, which we believe is fair and clearly argued.'
Customs and Excise said yesterday it had not yet had time to decide whether
to appeal.
The VAT argument is being watched with close interest by business car
operators and vehicle manufacturers.
</TEXT>
