<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Summit agrees action on cocaine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN ANTONIO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush and leaders from six Latin American nations yesterday
concluded a two-day drug summit in San Antonio, Texas, by announcing
measures to promote co-operation in their war against drugs, writes Damian
Fraser from San Antonio.
However, the US refused to give any new money to the Latin nations, despite
repeated requests from Peru for more aid. President George Bush said 'we are
dealing in a time of sparse resources. We don't have all the money to spend
on all the programmes we think are worthwhile.'
The seven nations did agree to set up a permanent structure for an annual
meeting to co-ordinate the fight against drugs. They will also seek to curb
the trade in chemicals necessary for the processing of cocaine, and help
each other in spotting and seizing aircraft used for drugs trafficking. They
announced their intention to seek further financial aid from Japan and
Europe to support the campaign.
