<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / Finnish coalition in favour of joining EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HELSINKI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FINLAND'S centre-right coalition government last night voted in favour of
applying to join the European Community. The Finnish parliament debates the
proposal next month is expected to approve making a formal membership
application on March 18.
A majority of ministers voted in favour of EC membership despite tensions
within the ruling Centre Party over the effect on Finnish agriculture. The
Centre Party traditionally has represented the interests of farmers, many of
whom fear that EC membership would mean cuts in generous state subsidies.
The government warned last night that Finnish agriculture would have to
become more competitive.
Finland, a member of the European Free Trade Association (Efta), hopes to
join Sweden and Austria in parallel entry negotiations.
A report commissioned by parliament predicted that EC membership would boost
economic growth, create 100,000 jobs over the next 10 years and lead to cuts
in taxes and consumer prices. A recent opinion poll showed that 51 per cent
of Finns favour EC membership while 40 per cent are against it.
The opposition Social Democrat Party is in favour of EC membership.
President Mauno Koivisto, who has constitutional responsibility for foreign
policy, backed EC membership in a speech earlier this month.
</TEXT>
