<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gold rose on the London bullion market after Comex opened higher as
buy-stops were triggered by local traders. 'It's a typical short covering
rally in a bear market. . . I think the range for the year has been Dollars
348 - Dollars 360 and that says it all really,' one London dealer said. The
market remains wary of the approach of the Islamic month of Ramadan from
March 5, during which period average gold prices have exceeded those of the
preceding month only once in the past seven years, UBS analyst Andy Smith
said. But this time round gold is entering Ramadan at the lowest levels
since 1986. Average prices in the month following Ramadan have usually also
been lower in the past seven years. At the London Metal Exchange copper and
aluminium prices eased back from their highs during late trading amid
reports that Russia had cancelled duties on metal exports. There was no
confirmation, but after the exchange closed a government adviser, speaking
in Moscow, said some Russian companies were receiving tax breaks. At the
close cash copper was Pounds 1,298.75 a tonne, up Pounds 7.25 on the day,
while cash aluminium was down Dollars 4 at Dollars 1,318.50 a tonne. The May
robusta coffee price ended Dollars 11 higher at Dollars 813 a tonne on
short-covering.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
