<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / International Company News: Amcor soars 138% in face of
recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MELBOURNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMCOR, the Australian paper and packaging group, yesterday reported a 138
per cent rise in net profits to ADollars 190.7m (Dollars 142.8m) for the
first half to December from ADollars 80m a year earlier, Reuter reports from
Melbourne.
Amcor said the result was highly satisfactory given that Australia was in
serious recession. Sales rose to ADollars 2.3bn in the half from ADollars
2.26bn. Earnings per share rose to 22.5 cents from 16.7 cents,and the
dividend is being raised to 14 cents a sharefrom 13 cents.
The profit rise was due to substantial capital spending in recent years,
strict cost control, plant rationalisation and expansion into profitable
overseas operations.
An abnormal gain of ADollars 78.6m was mainly due to the sale of 22.5m Mayne
Nickless shares for ADollars 8.05 a share, which realised a profit for the
group of ADollars 77m.
Amcor said cash-flow for the period was well ahead of last year and it had
about ADollars 200m cash on deposit.
Amcor said it was reaping the benefits of a conservative approach to
offshore expansion and was confident of continued improvement in results
from its overseas subsidiaries.
Although demand was firm in some segments of Amcor's business, particularly
aluminium beverage cans and business papers, sales volumes in most other
product categories showed little change.
Sales for container packaging in Australia, New Zealand and Canada rose 8.1
per cent to ADollars 679m in the half, while sales for fibre packaging rose
14.2 per cent to ADollars 600m.
The company said it expected further good results in the second six months.
'Directors hope to continue the progress made to date and, given no further
deterioration in Australian economic conditions, we expect to achieve
further good results in the January-June period,' it said. 'Should economic
activity expand, Amcor is poised for a period of strong growth worldwide.'
</TEXT>
