<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / British Gas agrees terms with OFT: Company to trim share of
industrial market and form pipeline subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS will announce details of an agreement with the Office of Fair
Trading in the next few days that will lead to the company halving its share
of the industrial gas market by 1995 and splitting off its pipeline and
storage division into a separate subsidiary, the company said yesterday.
The industry retains grave doubts about how British Gas will arrange the
sale of significant amounts of its gas to competitors, as is envisaged by
the OFT.
The first gas sales are due to begin in October. Some observers say that
without adequate regulation the auction may push prices higher in the UK.
The Office of Gas Supply, the industry regulator, has resisted any deal that
would lead to higher prices for domestic and industrial consumers.
British Gas yesterday reported an after-tax profit of Pounds 1.16bn for last
year. That compares with a profit of Pounds 1.21bn in the year from April
1990 to March 1991. Since the company has changed its financial year,
comparisons with previous figures are hard to make.
Mr Robert Evans, British Gas chairman, said yesterday the company gained
280,000 customers in 1991 and installed about 500,000 central heating
systems in spite of the recession.
However, Mr Evans said that the recession had affected some customers'
ability to pay and that outstanding debt from non-paying customers had risen
to Pounds 40m from about Pounds 30m the year before.
During the year, 150,000 additional customers had been forced by financial
difficulties to secure special payment arrangements. The company said that
slightly fewer than 1m households now pay by special arrangement.
The disconnection rate had dropped, Mr Evans said, to 18,000; the lowest
yearly rate recorded by the company.
In April, British Gas will have to work within the confines of a tough new
pricing formula for domestic customers imposed by its regulator. Mr Evans
said there would be no change in prices in April, 'but given another year
with low inflation and prices will be down in real terms'.
Sir James McKinnon, director general of Ofgas, said the fact that British
Gas saw profit from sales of gas to domestic customers rise by about Pounds
100m in 1991 demonstrated that it had been 'high time for a tariff review'.
The rise in domestic profits was offset by a small fall in earnings from the
industrial market, where the company lost about 25 per cent of its market
share to competitors by the end of 1991, bringing its market share down to
about 70 per cent.
Mr Evans said the company's capital expenditure for this year would be
Pounds 2.5bn - a record - most of which will be invested in the UK.
